Introduction and Overview

This report provides a detailed analysis of Johnson & Johnson (JNJ), a 491.26 B company, operating in the Drug Manufacturers - General industry. Would it be wise to invest in Johnson & Johnson at this moment? Let's see how well JNJ stock performs in the current market.

Here's What You Need to Know Right Now

The stock is currently trading at $203.90 (as of November 2025), and it's showing positive momentum, trading above both its 50-day and 200-day moving averages.

Analysts are cautious, with a 1-year price target of $200.82 (a potential -6.2% downside). However, there's significant volatility here (14.2% annualized), suggesting the potential for wide price swings.

Johnson & Johnson's fundamental story is nuanced. On one hand, the company benefits from solid revenue growth (up 6.80% YoY). On the other, it faces challenges with intense competition in its sector.

Company Description

Understanding the core business provides context for the following analysis. Johnson & Johnson, together with its subsidiaries, engages in the research and development, manufacture, and sale of various products in the healthcare field worldwide. It operates in two segments, Innovative Medicine and MedTech.

The Innovative Medicine segment offers products for various therapeutic areas, such as immunology, including rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and psoriasis; infectious diseases comprising HIV/AIDS;

neuroscience, consisting of mood disorders, neurodegenerative disorders, and schizophrenia; oncology, such as prostate cancer, hematologic malignancies, lung cancer, and bladder cancer; cardiovascular and metabolism, including thrombosis, diabetes, and macular degeneration;

and pulmonary hypertension comprising pulmonary arterial hypertension through retailers, wholesalers, distributors, hospitals, and healthcare professionals for prescription use. The MedTech segment provides electrophysiology products to treat heart rhythm disorders;

the heart recovery portfolio, which includes technologies to treat severe coronary artery disease requiring high-risk PCI or AMI cardiogenic shock; circulatory restoration products for the treatment of calcified coronary artery and peripheral artery diseases;

and neurovascular care that treats hemorrhagic and ischemic stroke. This segment offers an orthopaedics portfolio that includes products and enabling technologies that support hips, knees, trauma, spine, sports, and other;

surgery portfolios comprising advanced and general surgery technologies, as well as solutions for breast aesthetics and reconstruction; contact lenses under the ACUVUE brand;

and TECNIS intraocular lenses for cataract surgery. It distributes its products to wholesalers, hospitals, and retailers, as well as physicians, nurses, hospitals, eye care professionals, and clinics. The company was founded in 1886 and is based in New Brunswick, New Jersey.

Essentially, you're paying for quality - but quality doesn't come cheap.

Profitability and Growth

An analysis of the key metrics in JNJ's margin performance shows the company has solid control over its costs and prices. The company is successful in controlling its production costs, as shown by the gross margin of 68.36%, and it also profits well from its core operations, reflected in the 30.20% operating margin. A 34.64% EBITDA margin indicates JNJ is capable of generating strong cash flow from its operations before accounting for financing and tax strategies. All things considered, JNJ can hold onto around $27.260 in net profit for every $1 of its revenue over the last twelve months. While the business's revenue is increasing at an aggressive rate (6.80%), investors should monitor if this pace can be sustained without eroding profit margins.

JNJ's 31.92 B in EBITDA and 62.99 B in gross profit indicate its raw earning power, while the 25.12 B in net income reveals how effectively it converts that power into bottom-line results. The company appears to be balancing its pursuit of growth with the need to maintain profitability. Despite healthy gross margins, there is a significant difference between the company's gross and net margins (68.36% vs. 27.26%). This is likely due to high operating expenses, interest costs, or taxes, which are key areas for investors to watch. In the future, maintaining steady or improving margins will be critical. JNJ needs to defend its pricing power and control operating costs, as this will help sustain profitability, especially if revenue growth moderates.

Dividends and Shareholder Returns

Dividend Summary & Investor Implications

The company currently offers a $5.20 annual dividend per share, translating to a dividend yield of 2.55%‚Äîmeaning for every $100 invested, shareholders receive $5.20 in dividends annually. This yield is below the 5-year average of 2.79%, suggesting that either the stock price has risen (reducing the yield) or dividend growth hasn't kept pace with historical trends.

Key Observations & Analysis:

  • The payout ratio of 49.08% is healthy, indicating the company uses only ~49% of its earnings to fund dividends. This leaves ample room for future increases or reinvestment in growth.
  • The very low trailing yield of 3.00% hints at a recent dividend initiation or a special, non-recurring payout, warranting further checks for consistency.
  • Investors must own the stock before the upcoming ex-dividend date of 2025-11-25 to receive the next dividend.
  • The last stock split (2:1 in 2001) is outdated and likely irrelevant to the current valuation.

Investor Takeaway:

  • Income Investors: The dividend appears sustainable, but investors should monitor earnings and cash flow to ensure the payout remains well-supported.
  • Growth Investors: The company maintains a balance between shareholder returns and reinvestment, appealing to a 'growth and income' strategy.
  • Watch For: Announcements of dividend hikes (which could bring the yield closer to its historical average) or significant stock price changes that would alter the yield.

What This Means for Traders?

As long as JNJ holds above the 20-day SMA ($193.17), the bullish momentum could continue. However, a rapid rise can push the stock far from its averages, increasing the risk of a pullback.

Momentum Check ‚Äì Time to Be Cautious

The RSI at 100.0 is flashing a strong overbought signal. Historically, when the RSI crosses above 70-75, we often see a pullback before the next leg up. At the same time, the MACD histogram is positive, confirming the upward momentum is still in play.

Trading Strategy:

Aggressive traders might consider taking partial profits. Conservative traders should wait for the RSI to cool below 70 before considering new positions.

Final Verdict ‚Äì Should You Buy, Hold, or Sell?

Bottom Line: The technicals suggest the rally may be running out of steam short-term. While the long-term trend remains bullish, a correction seems plausible before the next major move. Trade carefully and wait for confirmation at key levels.
